Christmas was cut dramatically short for residents of a famous New York apartment building after its facade collapsed onto the sidewalk - forcing them to flee into the night.

The drama unfolded after part of a structural wall belonging to the O'Neill Building, on Sixth Avenue, crumbled as many of its occupants tucked into Christmas dinner on Tuesday evening.

Local authorities immediately evacuated the block amid fears the former department store - the city's first when built in 1887 - might buckle.

'We were given a few minutes to 
collect medication or anything we needed' before being ushered out,' 
resident Anna Backer told WNYW-Fox 5 TV.

